I mean, I can only imagine Jimmy was running the Legendary version of Rise of the Dark Realms, so he could have said "y'all deal with it" or wiped and then tried for it. I mean, he had just drawn 25 cards the turn before.
I was really confused about him playing Necropotence until I saw that play. It's kind of a genius include, actually.
If a table sees Necropotence, they're going to kill it. They have to.
But if they don't, you get to draw cards all game. If they do, then in response you set aside a ludicrous amount of cards... all of which end up in your graveyard.

text: So a couple of things. First, I think Ash Barrens is almost better than Wilds/Expanse unless you need lands to be sacrificed/destroyed or need landfall (or are on a super tight budget), Ash Barrens does functionally the same thing (costs 1, land comes in untapped, vs costing 0 but coming into play tapped) and has the upside of being able to just be played as a colorless source late game without a tempo hit.

Second, do you see a lot of Back to Basics, Ruination, Blood Moon? 20 basics is maybe a "correct" amount to run in a 3 color deck, but there's also some game theory at play there; if nobody is actually enforcing the rules so to speak, is there any need to play by them? Maybe you can get away with pulling a basic for it if you aren't being punished for running under 20.
